    from flask import Flask, render_template, request
    import openai

    app = Flask(__name__)
    openai.api_key = "ac-1234567890abcdef"


    @app.route("/", methods=["GET", "POST"])
    def home():
    captions = []
    hashtags = []
    if request.method=="POST":
    topic = request.form.get("topic")
    if topic:
    # AI call
    captions = openai.Completion.create(engine="text-davinci-003",prompt=f"Write 5 creative captions about {topic}",max_tokens=200).choices[0].text.split("\n")
    hashtags = openai.Completion.create(engine="text-davinci-003",prompt=f"Write 10 hashtags for {topic}",max_tokens=200).choices[0].text.split()
    return render_template("index.html", captions=captions, hashtags=hashtags)

    if __name__=="__main__":
    app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=81)

  5. OpenAI
    OpenAI offers cutting-edge AI models for various applications, including natural language processing and generation. Enhance your projects with state-of-the-art AI capabilities.
    Secret usage
    import os
    from openai import OpenAI
     
    api_key = os.environ['OPENAI_API_KEY']
    organization_id = os.environ.get('OPENAI_ORG_ID') # Optional
     
    client = OpenAI(api_key=api_key, organization=organization_id)
    Chat creation
    response = client.chat.completions.create(
    model="gpt-3.5-turbo",
    messages=[
    {"role": "system", "content": "You are a helpful assistant."},
    {"role": "user", "content": "Hello!"}
    ]
    )
     
    print(response.choices[0].message.content)
    Image generation
    response = client.images.generate(
    model="dall-e-3",
    prompt="A futuristic cityscape with flying cars",
    size="1024x1024",
    quality="standard",
    n=1,
    )
     
    image_url = response.data[0].url
    print(f"Generated image URL: {image_url}")
    Embedding generation
    response = client.embeddings.create(
    model="text-embedding-ada-002",
    input="The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog"
    )
    embedding = response.data[0].embedding
    print(f"Embedding vector (first 5 elements): {embedding[:5]}")
    API Key

    To get started, you'll need an API key from OpenAI. Visit the API keys page in your OpenAI account, generate a new key, and paste it below.

    OPENAI_API_KEY
    Organization ID(optional)

    For accounts associated with multiple organizations, you can specify the Organization ID to use. This is optional; if not provided, your default organization will be used.

    OPENAI_ORG_ID

    messages=[

    ]
    )
    print(message.content[0].text)
    Streaming response
    with client.messages.stream(
    model="claude-3-opus-20240229",
    max_tokens=1000,
    messages=[
    {"role": "user", "content": "Write a short story about time travel."}
    ]
    ) as stream:
    for text in stream.text_stream:
    print(text, end="", flush=True)
    Content classification
    message = client.messages.create(
    model="claude-3-opus-20240229",
    max_tokens=100,
    messages=[
    {"role": "user", "content": "Classify the sentiment of this text: 'I absolutely love this product!'"}
    ]
    )
    print(message.content[0].text)

  10. Google Sheets
    Google Sheets API allows you to read, write, and modify Google Sheets. This integration uses a service account for authentication, suitable for server-side applications.
    Authentication Setup
    import os
    import json
    from google.oauth2 import service_account
    from googleapiclient.discovery import build
     
    SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON = os.environ['GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON']
    service_account_info = json.loads(SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON)
     
    credentials = service_account.Credentials.from_service_account_info(
    service_account_info,
    scopes=['https://www.googleapis.com/auth/spreadsheets']
    )
     
    sheets_service = build('sheets', 'v4', credentials=credentials)
    Read from Google Sheets
    SPREADSHEET_ID = 'your-spreadsheet-id'
    RANGE = 'Sheet1!A1:B5'
     
    result = sheets_service.spreadsheets().values().get(
    spreadsheetId=SPREADSHEET_ID,
    range=RANGE
    ).execute()
     
    values = result.get('values', [])
    for row in values:
    print(row)
    Write to Google Sheets
    SPREADSHEET_ID = 'your-spreadsheet-id'
    RANGE = 'Sheet1!A1:B2'
    VALUES = [
    ['Name', 'Score'],
    ['Alice', 95],
    ]
     
    result = sheets_service.spreadsheets().values().update(
    spreadsheetId=SPREADSHEET_ID,
    range=RANGE,
    valueInputOption='USER_ENTERED',
    body={'values': VALUES}
    ).execute()
     
    print(f"{result.get('updatedCells')} cells updated.")
    Service Account JSON

    The entire contents of your Google Cloud service account JSON key file. This includes all the necessary information for authentication.

    Creating a Service Account

    1. Go to Google Cloud Console and sign in with your Google account.
    2. Select an existing project or create a new one (Click project dropdown > "New Project").
    3. Navigate to "IAM & Admin" > "Service Accounts" in the left sidebar.
    4. Click "+ CREATE SERVICE ACCOUNT".
    5. Enter a name and optional description, then click "CREATE AND CONTINUE".
    6. Grant appropriate permissions (e.g., "Editor" for Sheets access), then click "CONTINUE".
    7. (Optional) Grant users access, or click "DONE".
    8. In the service accounts list, click the three dots next to your new account > "Manage keys".
    9. Click "ADD KEY" > "Create new key", choose "JSON" format, and click "CREATE" to download the key file.
    10. Go to "APIs & Services" > "Dashboard", click "+ ENABLE APIS AND SERVICES" up top.
    11. Search for and enable "Google Sheets API". Add "Google Docs API" if you're also using Google Docs.
    12. Open the JSON key file you downloaded, copy its entire contents, and paste it into this field.

    Remember to keep your key secure and never share it or commit it to Git. Follow the principle of least privilege when assigning roles.

    Getting a Spreadsheet ID

    1. Open the Google Sheet you want to access.
    2. Look at the URL in your browser. It will be in this format: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/SPREADSHEET_ID/edit#gid=0
    3. The SPREADSHEET_ID is the long string of letters, numbers, and hyphens between '/d/' and '/edit'.

    IMPORTANT: Granting Spreadsheet Access to Your Service Account

    1. Find your service account's email address in the JSON key file (look for "client_email").
    2. Open your Google Sheet.
    3. Click the "Share" button in the top right corner.
    4. In the "Share with people and groups" field, paste your service account's email address.
    5. Set the permission to "Editor" if you need write access, or "Viewer" for read-only access.
    6. Uncheck the "Notify people" box (optional).
    7. Click "Send" or "Share" (depending on your Google Workspace settings).
    GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON
  11. Google Docs
    Google Docs API allows you to create, read, and modify Google Docs. This integration uses a service account for authentication, suitable for server-side applications.
    Authentication Setup
    import os
    import json
    from google.oauth2 import service_account
    from googleapiclient.discovery import build
     
    SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON = os.environ['GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON']
    service_account_info = json.loads(SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON)
     
    credentials = service_account.Credentials.from_service_account_info(
    service_account_info,
    scopes=['https://www.googleapis.com/auth/documents']
    )
     
    docs_service = build('docs', 'v1', credentials=credentials)
    Read from Google Docs
    DOCUMENT_ID = 'your-document-id'
     
    result = docs_service.documents().get(documentId=DOCUMENT_ID).execute()
    print(f"The title of the document is: {result.get('title')}")
     
    content = result.get('body').get('content')
    for element in content:
    if 'paragraph' in element:
    for run in element['paragraph']['elements']:
    if 'textRun' in run:
    print(run['textRun']['content'])
    Write to Google Docs
    DOCUMENT_ID = 'your-document-id'
     
    requests = [
    {
    'insertText': {
    'location': {
    'index': 1,
    },
    'text': 'Hello from the Google Docs API!'
    }
    }
    ]
     
    result = docs_service.documents().batchUpdate(
    documentId=DOCUMENT_ID,
    body={'requests': requests}
    ).execute()
     
    print(f"Document updated: {result.get('documentId')}")
    Service Account JSON

    The entire contents of your Google Cloud service account JSON key file. This includes all the necessary information for authentication.

    Creating a Service Account

    1. Go to Google Cloud Console and sign in with your Google account.
    2. Select an existing project or create a new one (Click project dropdown > "New Project").
    3. Navigate to "IAM & Admin" > "Service Accounts" in the left sidebar.
    4. Click "+ CREATE SERVICE ACCOUNT".
    5. Enter a name and optional description, then click "CREATE AND CONTINUE".
    6. Grant appropriate permissions (e.g., "Editor" for Docs access), then click "CONTINUE".
    7. (Optional) Grant users access, or click "DONE".
    8. In the service accounts list, click the three dots next to your new account > "Manage keys".
    9. Click "ADD KEY" > "Create new key", choose "JSON" format, and click "CREATE" to download the key file.
    10. Go to "APIs & Services" > "Dashboard", click "+ ENABLE APIS AND SERVICES" up top.
    11. Search for and enable "Google Docs API". Add "Google Sheets API" if you're also using Google Sheets.
    12. Open the JSON key file you downloaded, copy its entire contents, and paste it into this field.

    Remember to keep your key secure and never share it or commit it to Git. Follow the principle of least privilege when assigning roles.

    Getting a Document ID

    1. Open the Google Doc you want to access.
    2. Look at the URL in your browser. It will be in this format: https://docs.google.com/document/d/DOCUMENT_ID/edit
    3. The DOCUMENT_ID is the long string of letters, numbers, and hyphens between '/d/' and '/edit'.

    IMPORTANT: Granting Document Access to Your Service Account

    1. Find your service account's email address in the JSON key file (look for "client_email").
    2. Open your Google Doc.
    3. Click the "Share" button in the top right corner.
    4. In the "Share with people and groups" field, paste your service account's email address.
    5. Set the permission to "Editor" if you need write access, or "Viewer" for read-only access.
    6. Uncheck the "Notify people" box (optional).
    7. Click "Send" or "Share" (depending on your Google Workspace settings).
    GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON

  13. Discord
    Discord is a communication platform designed for creating communities. Integrate with Discord to send messages, manage servers, and enhance user engagement.
    Secret usage
    import os
    import discord
    from discord.ext import commands
     
    intents = discord.Intents.default()
    intents.message_content = True
    bot = commands.Bot(command_prefix='!', intents=intents)
    Bot setup and message handling
    @bot.event
    async def on_ready():
    print(f'We have logged in as {bot.user}')
     
    @bot.command()
    async def hello(ctx):
    await ctx.send('Hello!')
     
    bot.run(os.environ['DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN'])
    Slash command
    @bot.tree.command(name="greet", description="Greet a user")
    async def greet(interaction: discord.Interaction, user: discord.Member):
    await interaction.response.send_message(f"Hello, {user.mention}!")
     
    @bot.event
    async def on_ready():
    await bot.tree.sync()
    print(f'We have logged in as {bot.user}')
     
    bot.run(os.environ['DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN'])
    Sending embeds
    @bot.command()
    async def embed(ctx):
    embed = discord.Embed(title="Example Embed", description="This is an example embed.", color=0x00ff00)
    embed.add_field(name="Field 1", value="Value 1", inline=False)
    embed.add_field(name="Field 2", value="Value 2", inline=False)
    await ctx.send(embed=embed)
    Bot Token

    Create a Discord application, add a bot to it, and paste the bot token below. This token allows your bot to interact with Discord servers.

    DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN

  15. HubSpot
    HubSpot provides a comprehensive CRM platform with powerful API capabilities. Integrate HubSpot's features into your applications to manage contacts, deals, marketing campaigns, and more using secure private apps.
    Authentication setup
    import os
    from hubspot import HubSpot
     
    access_token = os.environ['HUBSPOT_ACCESS_TOKEN']
    client = HubSpot(access_token=access_token)
    Fetch contacts
    from hubspot import HubSpot
     
    access_token = os.environ['HUBSPOT_ACCESS_TOKEN']
    client = HubSpot(access_token=access_token)
     
    def get_all_contacts():
    all_contacts = []
    after = None
    while True:
    contacts_page = client.crm.contacts.basic_api.get_page(
    limit=100,
    after=after,
    properties=["firstname", "lastname", "email"]
    )
    all_contacts.extend(contacts_page.results)
    if not contacts_page.paging:
    break
    after = contacts_page.paging.next.after
    return all_contacts
     
    contacts = get_all_contacts()
    for contact in contacts:
    print(f"Name: {contact.properties['firstname']} {contact.properties['lastname']}")
    print(f"Email: {contact.properties['email']}")
    print("---")
    Access Token

    To get started, you'll need to create a private app in HubSpot. Go to Settings > Account Setup > Integrations > Private Apps. Create a new private app, select the necessary scopes, and generate your access token. Paste the token below.

    HUBSPOT_ACCESS_TOKEN
